Critics might oppose my previous statement that "neither feminism nor LGBTQ has opposed gender-centrism," claiming that "queer theory is against gender-centrism." I admit that queer theory is ontologically anti-gender-centric, as argued by #textcite(<Butler1990Gender>) that they do not consider "sex" (phenotypic sex) or gender to be natural, real or stable. Still, there is a huge difference between ontology and methodology.

#textcite(<Butler1990Gender>) advocated for a strategy of "repeating":

#quote(block: true)[
    The task is not whether to repeat, but how to repeat, or, indeed, to repeat and, through a radical multiplexing of gender, to displace the very gender norms that enable the repetition itself.
]

The issue is neither _whether_ to repeat nor _how_ to repeat, but _what_ to repeat. For example, drag is a kind of repetition, however, this is precisely because we have gender norms about "what clothes men/women should wear." Nobody would use a strange desk as a kind of "subversive repetition," because there is no gender norm about desks. This strategy recognises the gender norm's power to define the area and boundary of the battlefield. Even "subversive" repetition is still a "repetition," therefore operates within the boundaries defined by "gender." Queer theory is ontologically anti-gender-centric yet methodologically extremely gender-centric. The intended outcome of this strategy was to "displace the very gender norms" by showing their constructed and unstable nature. However, as the actual outcome, by constantly talking about and analysing gender, by "repeating" gender inside the boundary, it has reinforced "gender" as the central issue for understanding ourselves and society. "Gender" was originally just an external sociocultural construct, but it is now frequently used as a synonym of "gender identity," an internal psychological phenomenon, and one must define themself by interacting with gender. For example, Butler used the word "gender" interchangeably with "gender identity" in an interview @Williams2014Gender, which is a category error that confused an abstract sociological concept with a psychological phenomenon. #textcite(<Oberle2023Benefits>) is also a typical case, they argued that using the word _gender_ to describe plants "harms" transgender people. It is the same category error to claim that the borrowing of an abstract sociological concept, _gender_, will "harm" humans who possess a psychological phenomenon, _gender identity_.

Similarly, creating many new third-person pronouns has nothing to do with "affirming self-identification." It is only because of the gendered third-person pronouns in English (and other Indo-European languages). However, gendered third-person pronouns themselves are an unjustified arbitrary social norm. If somebody propose a new second-person pronoun and demand all people use it rather than "you" to communicate with them, their demand will definitely not be respected. The so-called "freedom" or "liberation" is permitted by the gender construct, therefore reproducing the gender norm itself.

Moreover, it constitutes a cultural invasion upon languages without gendered third-person pronouns. Chinese originally lacked gendered third-person pronouns. Before the New Culture Movement, 他 (_tā_, will be mentioned as "neutral _tā_" in the following text) referred to anyone, regardless of gender. During the Westernisation wave in the 20th century, Liu Bannong created 她 (_tā_, she, will be mentioned as "female _tā_" in the following text) in 1917 to mirror the gendered pronouns in European languages, especially English. This sparked controversy; for instance, the magazine _Women's Resonance_ (妇女共鸣) argued that replacing the "human" radical (亻) with the female radical (女) from the neutral _tā_ to create the female _tā_ dehumanised women. Nonetheless, the utility of the distinction, especially in translation and new literature, led to its widespread adoption. Ironically, some "modern Liu Bannongs" brainwashed by the West propose creating a "gender-neutral pronoun" to mirror English's _they_. I am not a linguistic purist. I completely accept reasonable loanwords. However, gendered pronouns is not a reasonable case. It is not a natural and equal language contact, but a linguistic pattern that continuously replicates in history: imitating English pronouns, making English almost the "upstream" (in the software engineering sense) of Chinese. It is clearly a continuation of the old binary gender system, playing the same role in intercultural relations, imposing the Western gender system onto third-world cultures. It is not a subversion or rebellion against power, but rather the newest and most sophisticated form of the old power structure -- gender-centric ideology.

Queer theory's strategy was to engage gender norms on the "battlefield" which was defined by itself. The unintended consequence of this engagement was that the battlefield itself -- the very concept of "gender" -- became more central, omni-encompassing, and ideologically powerful than ever before, attracting everyone to join it. The strategy recognised the prison's power to define its walls, and sought to "destabilise" them by painting them many colours, but not destroy and escape from it. The outcome was that the "colourful and comfortable" prison became more fundamentally entrenched, attracted more and more people to move in and reinforcing the core idea that one must be a prisoner. If a theory operates only within the field permitted by the existing social order, it is essentially defending this order, thus losing its ability to critique the social injustice.

Although Butler themself opposes identity politics, the aforementioned gender pluralism is arguably influenced by this strategy. Because they created a powerful cultural incentive: to treat all kinds of unconventional personal experiences and identities as a "gender", because it has made "gender" the most attractive "liberative" discourse. If "gender" were still strictly understood as a social construct (its original sociological definition), xenogender people would likely not see their "identity" as a "gender identity." They do so because "gender" is currently the most prominent and available discourse of resistance. This paradoxically expands the category of gender to encompass phenomena that might otherwise have been understood in different categories (e.g., as personality, philosophy, or simply as radical individuality). 
