In an interview with #textcite(<Williams2014Gender>), Butler claims that "some people really love the gender that they have claimed for themselves. If gender is eradicated, so too is an important domain of pleasure for many people. And others have a strong sense of self bound up with their genders, so to get rid of gender would be to shatter their selfhood." Similar viewpoints are also found in the analytical tradition: #textcite(<Cull2019Against>), who supports the aforementioned "gender pluralism," argued that "A genderless society is harmful to transgender people by refusing to recognise their identity." However, the fallacy is that Butler and Cull presumed the existence of "transgender people" as an immutable and transhistorical category that will persist in a society where the concept of gender no longer operates, which is typical gender essentialism. It is the same as saying, "We need to use pathogens to make vaccines, so eliminating pathogens would harm the patient's life," ignoring the fact that there will not be patients in an apathogenic environment.

I do not shy away from this point: according to my model, in a world where gender is abolished, transgender people will not exist. Cisgender people will also not exist. Because "assigned sex" and "gender identity" will not exist, which are necessary in the definition of "transgender" and "cisgender." However, this is not an elimination of contemporary transgender people, nor does it mean that healthcare for contemporary transgender people is not needed. Quite the contrary, this is based on a profound acknowledgement of the suffering of contemporary transgender people (including myself). The root cause of the suffering (such as gender dysphoria) and oppression is the social construct about gender. Transgender status is not an individual condition stemming from an "inner self" that requires medical care #footnote[I fully acknowledge that body representation incongruence is an internal body condition requiring medical treatment. However, as we previously argued, considering it "gender identity" is a category error. In my envision, one may just go to a doctor and say, "I have a persistent rejection of this part, it affects my life, and I want to remove it to resolve my suffering." ], but a serious political threat to our very existence. Insisting on "gender identity" is to treat only the symptoms while allowing the pathogen (the gender construct) to persist. True liberation is not achieved by merely managing the symptoms while allowing the pathogen to thrive. It requires eliminating the pathogen altogether. It is not to defend the identity of "transgender" but to achieve a world where such categories are no longer necessary to describe human experience. Gender abolitionism is the only systematic solution, as it correctly identifies the problem in the socialisation that shapes all individuals.

It is clearly impossible that something "someone finds meaning in" should be protected. Some housewives find meaning within the patriarchal gender division of labour; some users genuinely find joy in short videos; some fans really enjoy the movies produced by cultural industry ... Are all these things in need of protection? Therefore, "someone finds meaning in it" is not a sufficient condition of "it should be protected."

In fact, "eliminating" (in this specific sense) transgender status requires no grand social engineering like gender abolition. Simply stopping birth sex assignment is enough to dismantle the cisgender/transgender binary entirely, as their definitions are contingent upon the "assigned sex." Here lies the irony: if anything that invalidating  "transgender" condition is "transphobic," abolishing birth sex assignment invalidating "transgender" condition, then birth sex assignment is "transphobic." The transgender community should fight to protect birth sex assignment rather than opposing it. The original assumption leads to a contradiction, proving that Butler and Cull's opposition to gender abolitionism is logically invalid. It proves that a political proposal that logically invalids transgender condition does not necessarily harm transgender people, it can also be liberatory to us.

The two aforementioned points demonstrated that this theory paradoxically relies on the system it opposes. As I previously argued, this is precisely because of the ontology of post-structuralism. They do not believe that the objective knowledge of the external world is possible. Therefore, the goal is not to match an external truth, but to play with, subvert, and reconfigure the discourses we live within. By rejecting the premise of objective knowledge, they finally strengthened gender-centrism. In contrast, an objective understand of the reality is possible and desirable in scientific realism, which provides an unshakeable foothold for scientific and philosophical criticism and political resistance: the concept of "gender" causes most people's perception of the world to be inconsistent with this external, objective reality. So it must be abolished. Science reveals the "true nature" of the world, thereby stripping oppressive social systems of their legitimacy.

Ironically, #textcite(<Butler2025Who>) compared transphobia with climate change, environmental problems, which are, however, revealed by science. This means that Butler thought that science is able to establish truth and serve as a foundation of liberatory political ections, at least in some specific fields. It seems that Butler also respects science in these fields. Why cannot it play the same role in the gender issue?

